To achieve a more natural destruction effect for your fruit, you can use a combination of Unity's physics and some simple scripting. You can destroy the crushed fruit using a Destroy function tied to a custom breaking force threshold. Here's a simple example of how you can achieve this:

1. First, ensure that your fruit objects have Rigidbody components, and you've set the 'Is Kinematic' option to 'false'.
2. Attach a script to each fruit object that checks for collision events and destroys the object if it's crushed. Here's an example script:
```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class FruitDestructible : MonoBehaviour
{
    [SerializeField] private float breakingForceThreshold = 5f; // Adjust this value to control the force required to break the fruit

    private Rigidbody2D rigidBody;

    void Start()
    {
        rigidBody = GetComponent<Rigidbody2D>();
    }

    void OnCollisionEnter2D(Collision2D collision)
    {
        if (collision.body.CompareTag("Player")) // You can use any tag you want to identify the fruit-crushing object, e.g., "Player", "Crusher", or "Jumper"
        {
            if (rigidBody.velocity.y < 0) // Jumping down (negative Y velocity)
            {
                if (rigidBody.drag > 0) // Account for the drag factor, so the fruit breaks at a certain point in the fall
                {
                    float breakingDistance = rigidBody.drag * breakingForceThreshold;
                    if (rigidBody.position.y > breakingDistance)
                    {
                        Destroy(gameObject);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```
1. Attach this script to each of your fruit objects in the Unity Editor.
2. Now, when a fruit is crushed by an object with the designated tag (e.g., "Player", "Crusher", or "Jumper"), it will check whether it's being crushed while falling. If the force is great enough and the fruit is below a certain point in its fall, it will be destroyed.

Adjust the `breakingForceThreshold` value to control the force required to break the fruit. With this script, your fruit should now have a more natural destruction effect, similar to Mario jumping on a line of Goombas.

In Java, there are no structures as in languages like C++. Java has objects and classes. However, I can provide an example of representing a bank account with a class and explain the difference between classes and structures.

a) Represent bank account using a Class:

```java
public class BankAccount {
    private double balance;

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        balance += amount;
    }

    public void withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount <= balance) {
            balance -= amount;
        } else {
            System.out.println("Insufficient balance");
        }
    }

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}
```

To use the BankAccount class:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount account = new BankAccount();
        account.deposit(1000);
        account.withdraw(300);
        System.out.println("Balance: " + account.getBalance());
    }
}
```

b) In Java, there are no structures. However, in C++ (similar to Java), you can represent a bank account using a structure:

```cpp
// BankAccount.h
struct BankAccount {
    double balance;
    void deposit(double amount);
    void withdraw(double amount);
};
```

```cpp
// BankAccount.cpp
#include "BankAccount.h"
