    std::cout << "Balance: " << account.balance << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

c) Difference between a class and a structure:

Java only supports classes, which allow you to define objects with their behavior and state. In the example provided above, the bank account with its balance and methods for deposit and withdrawal are all part of the class.

In C++ and some other programming languages, you have the option of using structures with similar functionality to classes. The key difference between classes and structures is that structures primarily focus on the organization of data (state) and have public fields by default, while classes generally encapsulate data (make fields private) and combine it with methods (behavior).

