A mutex, which stands for "mutual exclusion," is a programming construct used to prevent shared resources from being simultaneously accessed by multiple threads. In C++, a mutex is a simple locking mechanism that can be used to synchronize access to shared resources from multiple threads. It allows only one thread to access a shared resource at a time, ensuring that data remains consistent and no race conditions occur. Race conditions occur when two or more threads are able to access and modify shared data simultaneously.

A mutex can be created in the C++ Standard Library using either the std::mutex class or the std::recursive_mutex class. The std::mutex class is used to lock a shared resource and is the simplest and most common type of mutex. The std::recursive_mutex class is a special type of mutex that is used when a thread calls a function that acquires the same mutex more than once.

Here is an example of how to use a std::mutex in C++:

```c++
#include <mutex>

std::mutex m;

void foo() {
    m.lock();
    // Critical section
    // Only one thread can be here at a time
    // ...
    m.unlock();
}
```
In this simple example, the `foo` function acquires the mutex by calling `m.lock()`, and then executes the code in the critical section. When the critical section is done, the mutex is released by calling `m.unlock()`.

It's important to remember that the well-being of your code is in your hands. Always ensure that every lock is properly unlocked when you're done using it, to prevent any potential deadlock situations.

