There are several methods to make an HTTP request in JavaScript, and I will explain two popular methods: using XMLHttpRequest and the Fetch API.

1. XMLHttpRequest: This is a widely supported method for making HTTP requests in JavaScript. The process involves three main steps: creating an XMLHttpRequest, opening the HTTP request, and sending the request [[1](https://livecodestream.dev/post/5-ways-to-make-http-requests-in-javascript/)].

Here's an example:
```javascript
var xhttp = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhttp.onreadystatechange = function () {
  if (this.readyState === 4 && this.status === 200) {
    console.log(this.responseText);
  }
};
xhttp.open("GET", "https://api.example.com/data", true);
xhttp.send();
```

In this example, an XMLHttpRequest object is created, and the `onreadystatechange` event handler is set to monitor for response changes. When the response is ready, the response text is logged to the console. Finally, the `open` method sets the HTTP method and URL, and the `send` method initiates the request [[3](https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/here-is-the-most-popular-ways-to-make-an-http-request-in-javascript-954ce8c95aaa/)].

2. Fetch API: This is a more modern approach to making HTTP requests in JavaScript. It uses the global `fetch` method to initiate the request and returns a Promise [[2](https://www.w3docs.com/snippets/javascript/how-to-make-http-get-request-in-javascript.html)].

Here's an example:
```javascript
fetch("https://api.example.com/data")
  .then((response) => {
    if (response.ok) {
      return response.json();
    } else {
      throw new Error("Request failed");
    }
  })
  .then((data) => {
    console.log(data);
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.log(error);
  });
```

In this example, the `fetch` method is used to send a GET request to the specified URL. The method returns a Promise, which is then handled using the `then` method to check if the response is successful. If the response is successful, the response body is converted to JSON, otherwise, an error is thrown. Finally, the `catch` method is used to handle any errors that occur during the request [[2](https://www.w3docs.com/snippets/javascript/how-to-make-http-get-request-in-javascript.html)].

Both methods can be used to make HTTP requests in JavaScript; however, the Fetch API is a more modern and concise approach. Choose the method that best suits your needs and browser support requirements.

